'''Graham Betchart''' (born April 30, 1978) is a [[sports psychology]] mental skills coach and current director of mental training for '''Lucid Performance'''.<ref name=autogenerated1>Uluc, Olgun. [http://www.foxsports.com.au/basketball/meet-graham-betchart-the-man-inside-the-head-of-likely-no-1-nba-draft-pick-ben-simmons/news-story/1d03173e83d0ba927149386993f2c84a "Meet Graham Betchart, the man inside the head of likely No. 1 NBA draft pick Ben Simmons"]. FoxSports.com. February 3, 2016. Retrieved July 6, 2016.</ref> He is known for the concept "Play Present," which teaches that an athlete needs to stay focused on the task at hand and immediately move on to the next play despite results or outcomes.<ref>Stein, Alan. [http://www.nhsbca.org/news_article/show/244655?referrer_id=752890 "Play Present"]. Nhsbca.org. April 5, 2013. Retrieved July 7, 2016.</ref> He is also noted for the "MVP" program (Mediate, Visualize, Positive affirmation), a sports psychology mental training tool, as well as "WIN" (What is Important Now), which asserts that a player can only control attitude, effort, and focus.<ref>Giles, Matthew. [https://sports.vice.com/en_us/article/meet-the-sports-psychologist-training-the-minds-of-the-nbas-top-draft-prospects "Meet the Sports Psychologist Training the Minds of the NBA's Top Draft Prospects"]. ''[[Vice (magazine)|Vice]]''. June 23, 2016. Retrieved July 7, 2016.</ref> Notable athletes Betchart has coached include [[Andrew Wiggins]], [[Karl-Anthony Towns]], and [[Ben Simmons]], the first overall picks for the [[2014 NBA draft|2014]], [[2015 NBA draft|2015]], and [[2016 NBA draft|2016]] [[National Basketball Association|NBA]] drafts, respectively.<ref name=autogenerated1 />

